name probably based on the element <i>bre-</i> ‘hill’, with the transferred sense ‘eminence’, i.e. ‘exalted one’.  See also  Bryan  . In Ireland there has also been some confusion with   O’Byrne   (  see  Byrne  )."],"variants":[{"name":"O’Briant","meanings":["Irish: variant of   O’Brien  ."]},{"name":"Bryan","meanings":["English and Irish: variant of   Bryant  .","Irish: shortened Anglicized form of <b>Ó Briain</b>, see   O'Brien  ."]},{"name":"O’Bryant","meanings":["Irish: variant of   O’Brien  ."]},{"name":"Byrne","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Irish Brendan, Eamon, Aidan, Liam, Niall, Declan, Eamonn, Fergus, John Patrick, Keelin, Kieran, Siobhan.","Irish: Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Ó Broin</b> ‘descendant of <i>Bran</i>’, a personal name based on <i>bran</i> ‘raven’. Bran was the name of a son of the King of Leinster, who died at Cologne in 1052, and also of the hero of an 8th century voyage tale.","Irish: in some cases, possibly from <b>Ó Birn</b> ‘descendant of <i>Biorn</i>’, Irish form of the Old Norse personal name <i>Bjǫrn</i>."]},{"name":"O’Byrne","meanings":["Irish: Anglicized form of Gaelic Ó Broin (  see  Byrne  )."]},{"name":"O’Brian","meanings":["Irish: variant spelling of   O’Brien  ."]},{"name":"O’Bryan","meanings":["Irish: variant spelling of   O’Brien  ."]},{"name":"O’Brion","meanings":["Irish: variant spelling of   O’Brien  ."]},{"name":"O’Bryon","meanings":["Irish: variant of   O’Brien  ."]}]},{"name":"Matilda","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Latinized form of a Germanic personal name derived from <i>maht</i>, <i>meht</i> ‘might’ + <i>hild</i> ‘battle’. This was the name of an early German queen (  895–968 ), wife of  Henry  the Fowler, who was noted for her piety and generosity. It was also the name of the wife of  William  the Conqueror and of the daughter of  Henry I  of England (  see  Maud  ). The name was introduced into England by the Normans, and this Latinized form is the one that normally occurs in medieval records, while the vernacular form <i>Maud</i> was the one in everyday use. <i>Matilda</i> was revived in England as a learned form in the 18th century."],"variants":[{"name":"Mathilda","meanings":["Old German: Mighty battle maid"]}]}],"lifeSummary":"Matilda O’Brien was born in 1360, in Ireland. She married Roland FitzEustace about 1394, in Castlemartin, County Kildare, Ireland. They were the parents of at least 2 sons and 1 daughter. She died in Castlemartin, County Kildare, Ireland."},"et":{"1360–":"1360–Surnud","1355–1404":"1355–1404","1381–1454":"1381–1454","1398–Female":"1398–Surnud","1400–Male":"1400–Surnud","1360–Female":"1360–Surnud","1404":"1404","1400":"1400","1454":"1454","1355":"1355","1398":"1398","about 1400":"umbes 1400","about 1398":"umbes 1398","1360":"1360","1381":"1381","about 1394":"umbes 1394",", , , Ireland":"Iirimaa","Castlemartin, County Kildare, Ireland":"Castlemartin, County Kildare, Iirimaa","Castlemartin,Kilcullen, Kildare, Leinster, Ireland":"Castlemartin, County Kildare, Iirimaa"},"fi":{"1360–":"1360–Kuollut","1355–1404":"1355–1404","1381–1454":"1381–1454","1398–Female":"1398–Kuollut","1400–Male":"1400–Kuollut","1360–Female":"1360–Kuollut","1404":"1404","1400":"1400","1454":"1454","1355":"1355","1398":"1398","about 1400":"noin 1400","about 1398":"noin 1398","1360":"1360","1381":"1381","about 1394":"noin 1394",", , , Ireland":"Irlanti","Castlemartin, County Kildare, Ireland":"Castlemartin, County Kildare, Irlanti","Castlemartin,Kilcullen, Kildare, Leinster, Ireland":"Castlemartin, County Kildare, Irlanti"},"fr":{"1360–":"1360–Décédée","1355–1404":"1355–1404","1381–1454":"1381–1454","1398–Female":"1398–Décédée","1400–Male":"1400–Décédé","1360–Female":"1360–Décédée","1404":"1404","1400":"1400","1454":"1454","1355":"1355","1398":"1398","about 1400":"environ 1400","about 1398":"environ 1398","1360":"1360","1381":"1381","about 1394":"environ 1394",", , , Ireland":"I